Case 2: `idx > 0`. Then `idx ≥ 1`. We can use the induction hypothesis. The left side is `(hd :: tl).set idx e).sum`. The right side is `(hd + tl.sum) - (hd :: tl)[idx] + e`.

To use the induction hypothesis, we need to relate `idx` to `tl`. If `idx ≥ 1`, then `idx - 1` is a valid index for `tl`.

So we can use the induction hypothesis on `tl` with index `idx - 1`.

The left side: `(hd :: tl).set idx e).sum`. If `idx ≥ 1`, then this is `hd + (tl).set (idx - 1) e).sum`. The sum is `hd + ((tl).set (idx - 1) e).sum`.

The right side: `(hd + tl.sum) - (hd :: tl)[idx] + e`. The element at `idx` is `tl[idx - 1]`. So the right side is `hd + tl.sum - tl[idx - 1] + e`.

By the induction hypothesis, `((tl).set (idx - 1) e).sum = (tl).sum - (tl)[idx - 1] + e`.

Therefore, the left side is `hd + ((tl).sum - (tl)[idx - 1] + e) = hd + tl.sum - (tl)[idx - 1] + e`.

